Entertainment lovers will soon be treated to the latest break dance moves on television following the conclusion of the regional auditions of the Glo Battle of the Year Nigeria. The auditions for the competition were recently wrapped up in Lagos,  Abuja, Enugu, Port Harcourt, Kaduna and Benin. At a media event hosted by Globacom on Thursday in Lagos, the company explained that the next steps of the competition will involve dance mentorship programme for all regional winners, and plans to air the entire show early next year to all Nigerians, as well as the semi-finals and finals of the show which will also be aired live on television. According to the telecommunications solutions provider, thousands of budding dancers stormed the various venues of the regional auditions to showcase their dancing skills as the quest to select Nigeria’s winner of the Glo the Battle of the Year Nigeria continues. The company said fans and judges present at the various venues of the regional auditions were delighted with dexterous dance moves, with local and international dance legends such as Poco Lee, Pinky Debbie, Izzy Odigie, Big Flo, Maxbuck, Dunamis, Franc Okwara, JC Jedor, Poxy (Cameroon), Gidnasty (USA), Menno (Netherlands) and Manuela (Germany) all taking part. They are also set to feature at the next stage of the competition. <img class="alignnone wp-image-645313" src="https://f5p3e9e4.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/VANGUARD.jpg" alt="" width="550" height="470" srcset="https://f5p3e9e4.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/VANGUARD.jpg 899w, https://f5p3e9e4.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/VANGUARD-300x256.jpg 300w, https://f5p3e9e4.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/VANGUARD-768x656.jpg 768w, https://f5p3e9e4.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/VANGUARD-24x21.jpg 24w, https://f5p3e9e4.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/VANGUARD-36x31.jpg 36w, https://f5p3e9e4.stackpathcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/VANGUARD-48x41.jpg 48w" sizes="(max-width: 550px) 100vw, 550px" /> Another contestant at the Abuja auditions, Mariam Lawal, stated that she has been dancing since she was ten, and is currently working as a dance teacher in a private secondary school in Kaduna. She said: “It will be awesome to make it to the semifinals and finals in Lagos. If I win, I would use the money to help the less privileged.” Also, Judah Wilson, a dance instructor who participated in the Lagos auditions, said it was his first time auditioning and he did not know what to expect. He added that it would be awesome to make it to the finals so he could show the nation his full talent. The fantastic surprises lined up for winners includes a total prize money of N84 million and a chance to represent Nigeria at the global stage of the competition.